{
  "What is the moment of inertia of a point mass of 3 kg located 2 m from the axis of rotation?": "",
  "1.5 kg·m²": "",
  "12 kg·m²": "",
  "6 kg·m²": "",
  "9 kg·m²": "",
  "I = mr² = 3 × 2² = 3 × 4 = 12 kg·m².": "",
  "What is the moment of inertia of a solid disk of mass 4 kg and radius 0.5 m about its central axis?": "",
  "0.5 kg·m²": "",
  "4 kg·m²": "",
  "1 kg·m²": "",
  "2 kg·m²": "",
  "I = ½MR² = ½(4)(0.25) = 0.5 kg·m².": "",
  "A thin hoop of mass 2 kg and radius 0.3 m rotates about its central axis. What is its moment of inertia?": "",
  "0.09 kg·m²": "",
  "0.36 kg·m²": "",
  "0.6 kg·m²": "",
  "0.18 kg·m²": "",
  "For a hoop: I = MR² = 2 × (0.3)² = 2 × 0.09 = 0.18 kg·m².": "",
  "Using the parallel axis theorem, if a disk has I_cm = 0.5 kg·m², mass 4 kg, and is rotated about an axis 1 m from its center, what is I?": "",
  "4.5 kg·m²": "",
  "2.5 kg·m²": "",
  "8.5 kg·m²": "",
  "Parallel axis theorem: I = I_cm + Md² = 0.5 + 4(1²) = 0.5 + 4 = 4.5 kg·m².": "",
  "A solid sphere has mass 5 kg and radius 0.2 m. What is its moment of inertia about a diameter?": "",
  "0.1 kg·m²": "",
  "0.2 kg·m²": "",
  "0.04 kg·m²": "",
  "0.08 kg·m²": "",
  "I = (2/5)MR² = (2/5)(5)(0.04) = 0.08 kg·m².": "",
  "A uniform thin rod of mass 3 kg and length 2 m is rotated about its center. What is its moment of inertia?": "",
  "I = (1/12)ML² = (1/12)(3)(4) = 1 kg·m².": "",
  "The same 3 kg, 2 m rod is rotated about one end. What is its moment of inertia?": "",
  "I = (1/3)ML² = (1/3)(3)(4) = 4 kg·m².": "",
  "Two point masses, 2 kg each, are connected by a massless rod 1 m long and rotate about the center. What is the total I?": "",
  "Each mass is 0.5 m from the center. I_total = m₁r₁² + m₂r₂² = 2(0.5)² + 2(0.5)² = 0.5 + 0.5 = 1.0 kg·m².": "",
  "Moment of inertia depends on which two factors?": "",
  "Mass distribution and axis of rotation": "",
  "Mass and velocity": "",
  "Angular velocity and radius": "",
  "Force and distance": "",
  "Moment of inertia depends on how mass is distributed and where the rotation axis is located. Moving mass farther from the axis increases I.": "",
  "A hollow sphere of mass 6 kg and radius 0.1 m has I about its center equal to:": "",
  "0.12 kg·m²": "",
  "0.024 kg·m²": "",
  "0.06 kg·m²": "",
  "For a hollow (thin-walled) sphere: I = (2/3)MR² = (2/3)(6)(0.01) = 0.04 kg·m².": "",
  "What is moment of inertia?": "",
  "The kinetic energy of a spinning object": "",
  "The resistance of a body to changes in its rotational motion; the rotational analog of mass": "",
  "The angular velocity of a rotating object": "",
  "The torque needed to maintain constant angular velocity": "",
  "Moment of inertia (I) is the rotational analog of mass. It quantifies how difficult it is to change an object's rotational motion, depending on mass distribution relative to the axis.": "",
  "What is the parallel axis theorem?": "",
  "I = ½MR² for all disks due to the well-established relationship between axis trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "I = I_cm + Md²; the moment of inertia about any axis equals the moment about a parallel axis through the center of mass plus Md²": "",
  "The moment of inertia is the same about all parallel axes regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "I = I_cm − Md² for any parallel axis in most scenarios involving axis factors": "",
  "The parallel axis theorem states I = I_cm + Md², where d is the distance between the center-of-mass axis and the new parallel axis. It always increases I relative to the center of mass.": "",
  "What is the perpendicular axis theorem?": "",
  "The moment of inertia is always largest about the perpendicular axis": "",
  "For a planar body: I_z = I_x + I_y, where z is perpendicular to the plane containing x and y": "",
  "I = MR² for any axis perpendicular to a disk": "",
  "I about any axis equals the sum of I about two other axes": "",
  "The perpendicular axis theorem applies to planar (flat) objects: I_z = I_x + I_y, where z is perpendicular to the plane and x, y are in the plane.": "",
  "What does 'radius of gyration' mean?": "",
  "The distance k from the axis at which a point mass M would have the same moment of inertia (I = Mk²)": "",
  "The actual radius of a rotating object": "",
  "Half the diameter of the rotating body": "",
  "The maximum radius of rotation before an object breaks apart": "",
  "The radius of gyration k is defined by I = Mk². It represents the effective distance from the axis at which the total mass could be concentrated to give the same I.": "",
  "What does it mean for moment of inertia to be an 'additive' quantity?": "",
  "All parts of an object contribute equally to I": "",
  "You can multiply the moments of inertia of parts": "",
  "Moment of inertia always increases when objects are combined": "",
  "The total I of a composite body equals the sum of I values of its individual parts about the same axis": "",
  "Moment of inertia is additive: for a composite object, I_total = I_1 + I_2 + ... about the same axis. This allows calculation of complex shapes by summing simpler components.": "",
  "What is a 'principal axis' of rotation?": "",
  "The axis with the maximum moment of inertia": "",
  "The axis perpendicular to the angular velocity": "",
  "Any axis through the center of mass": "",
  "An axis about which the object can rotate without wobbling; the products of inertia vanish": "",
  "A principal axis is one about which the angular momentum and angular velocity are parallel. Products of inertia are zero, and the object rotates without wobbling.": "",
  "What is the formula for the moment of inertia of a continuous body?": "",
  "I = Σ m_i r_i, as conventional continuous theory": "",
  "I = ∫ F dr when viewed through a simplified": "",
  "I = ∫ r² dm; the integral of r² over all mass elements": "",
  "I = M × R under most circumstances involving": "",
  "For a continuous mass distribution, I = ∫ r² dm, where r is the perpendicular distance from each mass element dm to the axis of rotation.": "",
  "What does 'mass distribution' refer to in the context of rotational inertia?": "",
  "The shape of the object only": "",
  "How the mass of an object is spread relative to the axis of rotation": "",
  "The density of the object": "",
  "The total mass of the object": "",
  "Mass distribution describes how mass is arranged relative to the rotation axis. Objects with more mass farther from the axis have larger moments of inertia.": "",
  "What is the difference between a solid cylinder and a hollow cylinder of the same mass and radius in terms of I?": "",
  "The solid cylinder has a larger I": "",
  "They have the same I": "",
  "It depends on the height of the cylinders": "",
  "The hollow cylinder has a larger I because its mass is concentrated farther from the axis": "",
  "Solid cylinder: I = ½MR². Hollow (thin-walled) cylinder: I = MR². The hollow cylinder has twice the I because all mass is at maximum distance from the axis.": "",
  "What does the term 'rotational inertia' emphasize?": "",
  "The angular momentum of the object": "",
  "An object's tendency to resist changes in its rotational state of motion": "",
  "The force required to stop rotation": "",
  "How fast an object rotates": "",
  "Rotational inertia emphasizes an object's resistance to angular acceleration. A larger I means more torque is needed to achieve the same angular acceleration.": "",
  "A potter's wheel is a solid disk of mass 40 kg and radius 0.3 m. What torque is needed to accelerate it from rest to 5 rev/s in 4 s?": "",
  "2π ≈ 6.3 N·m": "",
  "4.5π ≈ 14.1 N·m": "",
  "π ≈ 3.1 N·m": "",
  "0.9π ≈ 2.8 N·m": "",
  "I = ½MR² = ½(40)(0.09) = 1.8 kg·m². ω = 5 rev/s × 2π = 10π rad/s. α = ω/t = 10π/4 = 2.5π rad/s². τ = Iα = 1.8 × 2.5π = 4.5π ≈ 14.1 N·m.": "",
  "A figure skater (modeled as a cylinder, mass 50 kg, radius 0.2 m) spins with arms tucked. She extends her arms, increasing her effective radius to 0.6 m. By what factor does her moment of inertia change?": "",
  "6×": "",
  "3×": "",
  "27×": "",
  "9×": "",
  "I = ½MR². The ratio is R₂²/R₁² = (0.6)²/(0.2)² = 0.36/0.04 = 9. Her moment of inertia increases by a factor of 9.": "",
  "A 2 kg uniform disk (R = 0.15 m) is mounted on an axle 0.25 m from its center using the parallel axis theorem. What is I about the axle?": "",
  "0.3 kg·m²": "",
  "0.125 kg·m²": "",
  "0.1475 kg·m²": "",
  "0.0225 kg·m²": "",
  "I_cm = ½MR² = ½(2)(0.0225) = 0.0225 kg·m². I = I_cm + Md² = 0.0225 + 2(0.0625) = 0.0225 + 0.125 = 0.1475 kg·m².": "",
  "Two identical solid spheres (each 1 kg, radius 0.05 m) are connected by a 0.4 m massless rod and rotated about the center of the rod. What is I_total?": "",
  "0.082 kg·m²": "",
  "0.084 kg·m²": "",
  "Each sphere: I_cm = (2/5)(1)(0.0025) = 0.001 kg·m². Distance from center of rod to sphere center: d = 0.2 m. By parallel axis theorem: I_each = 0.001 + 1(0.04) = 0.041. I_total = 2 × 0.041 = 0.082 kg·m².": "",
  "A flywheel has I = 8 kg·m² and rotates at 300 RPM. What is its rotational kinetic energy?": "",
  "400π² ≈ 3,950 J": "",
  "1200 J": "",
  "3600π² ≈ 35,500 J": "",
  "200π² ≈ 1,974 J": "",
  "ω = 300 × 2π/60 = 10π rad/s. KE = ½Iω² = ½(8)(100π²) = 400π² ≈ 3,950 J.": "",
  "A composite object consists of a solid disk (mass 3 kg, radius 0.2 m) with a point mass of 1 kg attached at the rim. What is the total I about the disk's center?": "",
  "0.16 kg·m²": "",
  "0.10 kg·m²": "",
  "I_disk = ½(3)(0.04) = 0.06 kg·m². I_point = 1 × (0.2)² = 0.04 kg·m². I_total = 0.06 + 0.04 = 0.10 kg·m².": "",
  "A solid ball and a hollow ball of the same mass and radius roll down a ramp. Which reaches the bottom first and why?": "",
  "The solid ball, because it has a smaller moment of inertia relative to its mass (I = 2/5 MR² vs 2/3 MR²)": "",
  "It depends on the angle of the ramp": "",
  "The hollow ball, because it has less rotational inertia": "",
  "They arrive at the same time": "",
  "The solid ball has I = (2/5)MR² while the hollow ball has I = (2/3)MR². A smaller I/MR² ratio means less energy goes into rotation and more into translation, so the solid ball accelerates faster.": "",
  "An engineer needs to design a flywheel with I = 2 kg·m². She can use either a solid disk or a thin hoop. If the mass is 10 kg, what radius does each require?": "",
  "Disk: 0.63 m; Hoop: 0.45 m": "",
  "Disk: 0.45 m; Hoop: 0.63 m": "",
  "Both require 0.45 m": "",
  "Disk: 0.45 m; Hoop: 0.32 m": "",
  "Disk: I = ½MR² → R = √(2I/M) = √(4/10) = √0.4 = 0.632 m. Hoop: I = MR² → R = √(I/M) = √(2/10) = √0.2 = 0.447 m. The hoop needs a smaller radius since all mass is at the rim.": "",
  "A 0.5 kg record (thin disk, R = 0.15 m) on a turntable is acted on by a frictional torque of 0.003 N·m. Starting at 33⅓ RPM, how long does it take to stop?": "",
  "3.27 s": "",
  "0.65 s": "",
  "1.97 s": "",
  "6.54 s": "",
  "I = ½(0.5)(0.0225) = 0.005625 kg·m². ω₀ = 33.33 RPM × 2π/60 = 3.49 rad/s. α = τ/I = 0.003/0.005625 = 0.533 rad/s². t = ω₀/α = 3.49/0.533 ≈ 6.54 s.": "",
  "A uniform door (mass 12 kg, width 0.9 m) is modeled as a thin rectangular slab rotating about its hinges. What is its moment of inertia? (I = ⅓ML² for a rod about one end)": "",
